Creating a simple Gioui golang todos app involves several steps. Gioui is a modern UI library for Golang that uses GPU-efficient rendering techniques.

1. Install the Golang and Gioui library: Make sure you have Golang installed on your system, preferably the latest version. You can get it from [here](https://golang.org/doc/install). Then, install the Gioui library using the following command:

   ```
   go get gioui.org/cmd/gio@latest
   ```

2. Create a file called `main.go` and open it in your favorite text editor for Golang. Here's a simple todo app that you can use as a starting point:

   ```go
   package main

   import (
   	"gioui.org/app"
   	"gioui.org/layout"
   	"gioui.org/unit"
   	"gioui.org/widget"
   )

   func main() {
   	go func() {
   		w := app.NewWindow(app.Title("Todos"), app.Size(unit.Dp(320), unit.Dp(480)))
   		todos := make([]string, 0)
   		newTask := &widget.Editor{}
   		list := &layout.List{}
   		for e := range w.Events() {
   			if e, ok := e.(app.UpdateEvent); ok {
   				gtx := layout.NewContext(&e.Config, e.Queue, e.Size)
   				inputField := layout.Rigid(
   					func(gtx layout.Context) layout.Dimensions {
   						newTask.Layout(gtx, &e.Config)
   						if newTask.Submit() {
   							text := newTask.Text()
   							todos = append(todos, text)
   							newTask.SetText("")
   						}
   						return layout.Dimensions{}
   					})
   				todoList := layout.Flexed(1,
   					func(gtx layout.Context) layout.Dimensions {
   						return list.Layout(gtx, len(todos), func(gtx layout.Context, index int) layout.Dimensions {
   							text := todos[index]
   							widget.Label{Align: layout.Start}.Layout(gtx, &e.Config, text)
   							return layout.Dimensions{}
   						})
   					})
   				layout.Flex{
   					Axis:    layout.Vertical,
   					Spacing: layout.SpaceEvenly,
   				}.Layout(gtx, inputField, todoList)
   				w.Update(gtx)
   			}
   		}
   	}()

   	app.Main()
   }
   ```

3. Compile and run the app using the Gioui command:

   ```
   gio run main.go
   ```

The provided example creates a simple todo app with an editor for entering new tasks and a list to display the existing tasks. Feel free to extend and modify the example to meet your specific requirements.

To learn more about the Gioui library, check out the [Gioui documentation](https://gioui.org/docs/getting-started).

Creating a simple Quran reading app in Golang using the Al-Quran Cloud API can be done by following these steps.

1. Install the required packages:

You will need the Gorilla Mux package for API handling and JSON parsing. To install Gorilla Mux, run the following command:

```bash
go get -u github.com/gorilla/mux
```

2. Prepare the code:

Here is a complete code example for implementing the Quran reading app:

```go
package main

import (
	"encoding/json"
	"fmt"
	"io/ioutil"
	"net/http"
	"strings"

	"github.com/gorilla/mux"
)

type Ayah struct {
	Text string `json:"text"`
}

type Data struct {
	Ayahs []Ayah `json:"ayahs"`
}

type ApiResponse struct {
	Data Data `json:"data"`
}

func FetchAyahs(surah int) (string, error) {
	response, err := http.Get(fmt.Sprintf("https://api.alquran.cloud/v1/surah/%d", surah))
	if err != nil {
		return "", err
	}
	defer response.Body.Close()

	body, err := ioutil.ReadAll(response.Body)
	if err != nil {
		return "", err
	}

	apiResponse := ApiResponse{}
	err = json.Unmarshal(body, &apiResponse)
	if err != nil {
		return "", err
	}

	arabicText := []string{}
	for _, ayah := range apiResponse.Data.Ayahs {
		arabicText = append(arabicText, ayah.Text)
	}

	return strings.Join(arabicText, "\n"), nil
}

func main() {
	r := mux.NewRouter()

	r.HandleFunc("/surah/{id:[0-9]+}", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
		vars := mux.Vars(r)
		surahID := atoi(vars["id"])

		ayahs, err := FetchAyahs(surahID)
		if err != nil {
			http.Error(w, "Failed to fetch Ayahs", http.StatusInternalServerError)
			return
		}

		w.WriteHeader(http.StatusOK)
		w.Write([]byte(ayahs))
	})

	http.ListenAndServe(":8000", r)
}
```

3. Build and run the application:

To build the application, run the following commands:

```bash
go build main.go
```

To run the application, simply execute the binary that was created in the previous step:

```bash
./main
```

4. Use the application:

Start the application, and access it using a browser or any API client (like Postman). Make a GET request to the following endpoint to get the Arabic text for any Surah:

```
http://localhost:8000/surah/{SURAH_NUMBER}
```

Replace `{SURAH_NUMBER}` with the desired Surah number (1 to 114). It will return the Arabic text as a plain-text response.

That's all! You now have a simple Golang app that can read the Arabic text of any Surah in the Quran using the Al-Quran Cloud API.

Here is an example code in Golang using Fiber as framework:

```
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"log"

	"github.com/gofiber/fiber/v2"
	"github.com/spf13/viper"
)

func main() {
	app := fiber.New()

	// Load configuration
	viper.SetConfigFile("config.json")
	err := viper.ReadInConfig()
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("Error loading config: %v\n", err)
	}

	// Define routers
	protect := app.Group("/protect")
	verify := app.Group("/verify")

	// Handlers for routers
	protect.Get("/", func(c *fiber.Ctx) error {
		return c.SendString("Protected content")
	})

	verify.Get("/", func(c *fiber.Ctx) error {
		return c.SendString("Verification page")
	})

	// Start server
	port := viper.GetInt("port")
	if port == 0 {
		port = 8000 // default port
	}

	addr := fmt.Sprintf(":%d", port)
	err = app.Listen(addr)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("Error starting server: %v\n", err)
	}
}

```

In this example, we loaded a configuration file `config.json` using the module `viper`. We defined two routers `protect` and `verify` with respective path `/protect` and `/verify`. And we implemented handlers for these routers to send simple responses. Finally, we started the server using the port defined in the configuration file or the default port `8000`.

To run this code, you need to install the module `fiber` and `viper`:

```
go get github.com/gofiber/fiber/v2
go get github.com/spf13/viper
```

And create a configuration file `config.json` with the following content:

```
{
    "port": 8000
}
```

You can change the value of the port to any other value as you like. Then, you can run the code using the following command:

```
go run main.go
```

