可以使用 bufio 包中的 Scanner 函数来实现按行循环读取文本。

示例代码如下：

```go
package main

import (
    "bufio"
    "fmt"
    "os"
)

func main() {
    // 打开文本文件
    file, err := os.Open("test.txt")
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Println("打开文件出错:", err)
    }
    defer file.Close()

    // 创建一个 Scanner 对象来读取文件
    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(file)

    // 按行循环读取文本内容
    for scanner.Scan() {
        fmt.Println(scanner.Text())
    }

    // 检查读取过程中是否有错误发生
    if err := scanner.Err(); err != nil {
        fmt.Println("读取文件出错:", err)
    }
}
```

注意事项：

- 在读取完毕后要及时关闭文件，可以使用 defer 关键字来延迟执行 Close 操作。
- 在循环读取过程中可以使用 Scanner 对象的 Err 方法来检查是否发生了读取错误。

Yes, it is thread-safe to read from a single channel in multiple go routines in Golang. The go routines will synchronize on the channel, ensuring that only one go routine will receive a value at a time. This is one of the core design principles of Go's concurrency model, and channels are designed with built-in synchronization mechanisms to enable safe communication between go routines.

Here's an example illustrating multiple go routines reading from a single channel:

```go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "sync"
)

func main() {
    ch := make(chan int, 10)

    go func() {
        for i := 0; i < 10; i++ {
            ch <- i
        }
        close(ch)
    }()

    var wg sync.WaitGroup
    wg.Add(3)

    for i := 1; i <= 3; i++ {
        go func(id int) {
            defer wg.Done()
            for v := range ch {
                fmt.Printf("Go routine %d received value: %d\n", id, v)
            }
        }(i)
    }

    wg.Wait()
}
```

In this example, there are three go routines reading from the same channel `ch`, and the channel is meant for communication between the main go routine and the three other go routines. The `sync.WaitGroup` is used to make sure the main go routine waits for all other go routines to finish before exiting.

Keep in mind, when multiple go routines read from a single channel, the order in which they read might not be deterministic, so you might get different orders of output each time you run the program.

