Here's an example of how you can apply a fade-in and fade-out effect to a custom font that lasts one second:

```
import java.awt.AlphaComposite;
import java.awt.Font;
import java.awt.Graphics;
import java.awt.Graphics2D;
import java.awt.RenderingHints;
import java.awt.image.BufferedImage;
import java.io.IOException;
import javax.imageio.ImageIO;
import javax.swing.JFrame;
import javax.swing.JPanel;

public class FontDemo {

   private static final int WIDTH = 300;
   private static final int HEIGHT = 150;
   private static final int ANIMATION_DELAY = 500;

   public static void main(String[] args) {

       // Load TTF font file
       Font customFont = null;
       try {
           customFont = Font.createFont(Font.TRUETYPE_FONT, FontDemo.class.getResourceAsStream("example.ttf"));
       } catch (Exception ex) {
           System.err.println("Font not loaded!");
       }

       // Create a panel with the custom font
       JPanel panel = new BlendingPanel(customFont, ANIMATION_DELAY);

       // Create a frame to display the panel
       JFrame frame = new JFrame("Custom Font Demo");
       frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
       frame.getContentPane().add(panel);
       frame.pack();
       frame.setLocationRelativeTo(null);
       frame.setVisible(true);
    }

    private static class BlendingPanel extends JPanel {

        private BufferedImage image;
        private Font font;
        private int animationDelay;

        public BlendingPanel(Font font, int animationDelay) {
            super();
            this.font = font;
            this.animationDelay = animationDelay;
        }

        @Override
        public void paintComponent(Graphics g) {
            super.paintComponent(g);
            Graphics2D g2 = (Graphics2D) g;
            g2.setRenderingHint(RenderingHints.KEY_TEXT_ANTIALIASING, RenderingHints.VALUE_TEXT_ANTIALIAS_ON);

            // Calculate transparency level
            long startTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
            long currentTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
            float alpha = 0.0f;
            while (currentTime - startTime < animationDelay) {
                alpha = (float) (currentTime - startTime) / animationDelay;
                repaint();
                currentTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
            }
            alpha = 1.0f;
            while (currentTime - startTime < animationDelay * 2) {
                alpha = 1.0f - (float) (currentTime - startTime - animationDelay) / animationDelay;
                repaint();
                currentTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
            }
            alpha = 0.0f;

            // Draw text with blending effect
            g2.setFont(font);
            g2.setComposite(AlphaComposite.getInstance(AlphaComposite.SRC_OVER, alpha));
            g2.drawString("This is an example text in custom font", 20, 80);
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, we create a custom JPanel class called `BlendingPanel` that fades the text in and out using a `while` loop to calculate the transparency level. The `animationDelay` variable controls the time it takes for the blending effect to complete, which is set to 500 milliseconds in this case.

The `repaint()` method is used to redraw the panel at regular intervals during the animation. The `AlphaComposite` class is used to apply the blending effect to the text, with a gradually increasing and decreasing transparency level.

You may adjust the delay, font, and text properties as needed.

